<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-782-579  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 782 579.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  June 21 1989 n109 p23(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business and Computer Publications1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Borland ships Reflex upgrade. (Borland International Inc.)andO;(product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Borland International Inc. (product enhancement).andO;Product:   Reflex 2.0 (Data base management system) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionData Base Management SystemsSoftware PackagesUpgrading.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Borland ships Reflex upgrade Borland has begun shipping a major upgrade toReflex, its low-end flat file database product.andP;  The company hopes to clawback market share it is thought to have lost to Symantec's Qandamp;A program.andM;Reflex 2.0 is the first upgrade to the product since it made its debut in1986.andP;  This, says Borland US, has enabled Symantec to leap ahead of thecompetition by updating Qandamp;A and adding word processing, natural languages andlook-up facilities -- all of which are unavailable in Reflex 1.0.andM;But Borland is convinced that its new version, priced at 250 pounds sterling,will topple Qandamp;A from the leading position -- partly because Reflex 2.0 isunique in offering object-orientated techniques, which are said to use memorymore efficiently than a traditional language.andM;Among the program's other features are support for databases up to the DOSfile limit and a Quick Report option, which gives details on spreadsheetfiles that users intend to import into Reflex.andM;In addition to improved graphics, Reflex is now claimed to provide a numberof facilities that Qandamp;A does not, such as multiple views, hotlinked windowsand crosstabs.andM;Yet Symantec's UK managing director, Michael Skok, remains confident that Qandamp;Aversion 3.0 has more to offer corporate customers, despite the productcosting 30 pounds sterling more than Reflex.andM;&quot;The corporate marketplace demands multi-access to the network.andP;  They requiremulti-user file and record locking, as well as password protection.andM;These features are not provided in Reflex 2.0,&quot; Skok claims.andM;Borland's UK managing director, Denis Moran, said that his company's productis pitched more towards smaller companies and independent professionals.andM;&quot;It's for people who don't want to learn about multiple files and relationaltheory, but who need to file, retrieve and analyse information quickly forthings like customer lists and mail shots,&quot; he explained.andM;Reflex's existing user base is expected to provide the initial market forBorland's new version.andP;  The cost to upgrade from Reflex 1.0 is 75 poundssterling.andO;</TEXT></DOC>